What you describe Jim can be done in the sql libraries that have been
developed on my project.  It&#39;s not that simple, you&#39;ll have to modify
existing code, but it comes in useful for lots of reasons.  Basically...

public class ConnectionPool
{
    public JDBCConnection getJDBCConnection(){...} 
    public void returnConnection( Connection ret ) { ... }
    public void commit() { do validation }
}

public class JDBCConnection implements java.sql.Connection
{
    // both methods do the same thing, just have different return types
    public JDBCStatement createJDBCStatement(){ ... } 
    public Statement createStatement(){ ... }}
}

What is going on here is that I have a custom SQL package.  For each
interface in java.sql I have a class which implements that interface and
acts as a wrapper around the connection, statement, resultset, etc. objects
that are returned by the driver.

For each method we add another, so as well as createStatement() we also have
createJDBCStatement(), this allows us to return references to the concrete
type, not just the interface.  This step is not required.

So now that we have a whole set of wrappers we can add monitoring code to
count open resultsets and such like.

Dave

